Defining and Applying Permissions with RBAC
Objectives
Define role-based access controls and apply permissions to users.
. What is RBAC?
RBAC = Role-Based Access Control
It is the system used by Kubernetes and OpenShift to control who can do what in the cluster.
It answers:
Who can perform which action on which resource
Example:
User	Action	Resource
developer	create	pods
admin	delete	projects
viewer	get	services
________________________________________
2. Authentication vs Authorization
These are two different steps.
Authentication
Verifies identity
Example:
username + password
token
certificate
Command example:
oc login -u developer -p developer
________________________________________
Authorization
Determines permissions.
Example:
Can the user create pods?
Can the user delete projects?
Authorization in OpenShift is implemented using RBAC.
________________________________________
3. RBAC Components
RBAC works using three objects.
Object	Meaning
Rule	Defines allowed actions
Role	Collection of rules
Binding	Assigns role to user or group
________________________________________
3.1 Rule
A rule defines:
action + resource
Example rule:
create pods
delete services
get deployments
Example structure:
verbs: create
resources: pods
________________________________________
3.2 Role
A Role is a set of rules.
Example role:
Developer Role
 ├ create pods
 ├ update deployments
 └ view services
Users can have multiple roles.
Example:
developer = view + edit
________________________________________
3.3 Binding
A Binding connects:
User → Role
Group → Role
ServiceAccount → Role
Example:
developer → edit role
This is called a RoleBinding.
________________________________________
4. RBAC Scope in OpenShift
OpenShift RBAC has two levels.
Level	Scope
Cluster RBAC	entire cluster
Local RBAC	single project
________________________________________
Cluster RBAC
Applies to entire cluster.
Objects:
ClusterRole
ClusterRoleBinding
Example permissions:
create nodes
delete projects
view cluster status
________________________________________
Local RBAC
Applies to one namespace/project only.
Objects:
Role
RoleBinding
Example:
developer can deploy apps
but only inside project "myapp"
________________________________________
5. RBAC Hierarchy
Cluster
   │
   ├ ClusterRole
   ├ ClusterRoleBinding
   │
Project
   │
   ├ Role
   └ RoleBinding
Cluster roles can also be used inside projects.
________________________________________
6. Managing RBAC Using CLI
Cluster administrators usually use:
oc adm policy
Project administrators use:
oc policy
________________________________________
7. Add Cluster Role to User
Command:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-role username
Example:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin john
Meaning:
john → full cluster access
Equivalent to superuser.
________________________________________
8. Remove Cluster Role
Command:
oc adm policy remove-cluster-role-from-user cluster-role username
Example:
oc adm policy remove-cluster-role-from-user cluster-admin john
Meaning:
john is no longer cluster admin
________________________________________
9. Check Permissions (who-can)
Very useful command.
oc adm policy who-can ACTION RESOURCE
Example:
oc adm policy who-can delete user
Result shows:
users/groups that can delete users
Another example:
oc adm policy who-can create pods
________________________________________
10. Default Roles in OpenShift
OpenShift already provides many built-in roles.
________________________________________
cluster-admin
superuser
Can:
create nodes
delete projects
manage cluster
everything
Command to assign:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin username
________________________________________
admin
Project administrator.
Can:
manage project resources
create quotas
add users
But cannot manage the whole cluster.
________________________________________
edit
Developer role.
Can:
create deployments
create services
update pods
delete applications
Cannot:
change quotas
manage permissions
________________________________________
view
Read-only access.
Can:
view pods
view services
view deployments
Cannot:
create or modify resources
________________________________________
cluster-reader
Read access to most cluster objects.
Useful for:
monitoring systems
auditing
________________________________________
basic-user
Allows users to:
view projects
view users
Very minimal permissions.
________________________________________
self-provisioner
Allows users to:
create their own projects
Example command:
oc new-project myproject
This works only if user has self-provisioner role.
________________________________________
11. Assign Role Inside a Project
Project admins use:
oc policy add-role-to-user
Example:
oc policy add-role-to-user edit dev -n wordpress
Meaning:
User: dev
Role: edit
Project: wordpress
So dev can:
create deployments
create services
update applications
But only inside wordpress project.
________________________________________
12. Remove Project Role
Command:
oc policy remove-role-from-user role user -n project
Example:
oc policy remove-role-from-user edit dev -n wordpress
________________________________________
13. User Types in OpenShift
OpenShift has three main user types.
________________________________________
1 Regular Users
These are human users.
Examples:
developer
admin
student
Represented by:
User object
________________________________________
2 System Users
Created automatically by OpenShift.
Examples:
system:admin
system:node:node1
system:openshift-registry
Used internally by cluster components.
All system users start with:
system:
________________________________________
3 Service Accounts
Used by applications and pods.
Pods cannot login like users.
Instead they use service accounts.
Example:
system:serviceaccount:namespace:account
Example:
system:serviceaccount:default:builder
________________________________________
View Service Accounts
oc get sa
Example output:
builder
default
deployer
________________________________________
14. Groups in OpenShift
A group is a collection of users.
Instead of assigning roles to each user:
user1
user2
user3
You assign role to the group.
Example:
developers group
________________________________________
Create Group
oc adm groups new lead-developers
Group created.
________________________________________
Add User to Group
oc adm groups add-users lead-developers user1
Now:
lead-developers
 └ user1
If the group has role edit, user1 automatically gets that role.
________________________________________
15. Authorization Flow
Full process:
User login
     ↓
Authentication
     ↓
User identity verified
     ↓
RBAC policies checked
     ↓
ClusterRoleBindings
     +
RoleBindings
     ↓
Permission granted or denied
________________________________________
16. Example Scenario
User:
developer
Command:
oc create deployment app
System checks:
Does developer have "create deployments" permission?
If:
RoleBinding → edit role
Then:
Allowed
Otherwise:
Forbidden
Example error:
Error from server (Forbidden)
